          "body": "What follows is one of Scripture's most sustained and unsettling catalogs of divine sovereign reversals. It is not a list of God's blessings — it is a list of God's dismantlings. He tears down and it cannot be rebuilt; He imprisons and there is no release (12:14). He controls the waters absolutely — drought and flood at will (12:15). He holds the deceived and the deceiver alike (12:16). Then the parade of the humiliated begins: counselors stripped barefoot, judges made fools (12:17); kings' bonds loosened and their dignity reversed into the belt of a servant or captive (12:18); priests stripped (12:19); the trusted deprived of speech, elders stripped of discernment (12:20); nobles covered with contempt, the strong disarmed (12:21). The significance of this catalog in the context of the dialogue cannot be overstated. The friends have been arguing that God rewards the righteous and punishes the wicked — a stable, predictable moral economy. Job's response is to point to God's actual governance of history: counselors, judges, kings, priests, elders, nobles — every human office of authority, wisdom, and sacred standing is subject to sovereign reversal. None of these categories is defined by moral failure in Job's account. God operates in ways that transcend the tidy moral economy the friends have constructed."
